[3.3 Basic Structure of SQL Queries]
    - SQL query consists of three clauses: select, from, and where

    (3.3.1 Queries on a Single Relation)
        - select distinct: elimination of duplicates
        - select all: allow duplicates
            -> but "select" duplicate retention is the default
        - "and", "or", and "not" in the "where" clause possible

    (3.3.2 Queries on Multiple Relations)
        - SQL Query can be understood as follows:
            1) Generate a Cartesian product of the relations listed in the "from" clause.
            2) Apply the predicates specified in the "where" clause on the result of Step 1.
            3) Output the attirubtes (or results of expressions) specified in the "select" clause.
